tspan.tspan: The goal of the IEEE International Conference on Autonomic
Computing and Self-Organizing Systems (ACSOS) is to provide
a forum for sharing the latest research results, ideas and
experiences in autonomic computing, self-adaptation and self-
organization. ACSOS was founded in 2020 as a merger of the
IEEE International Conference on Autonomic Computing (ICAC)
and the IEEE International Conference on Self-Adaptive and
Self-Organizing Systems (SASO).
We invite novel contributions related to the fundamental understanding of autonomic computing, self-adaption
and self-organization along with principles and practices of their engineering and application. The topics of
interest include, but are not limited to:
Resource Management in Data Centers and Cloud Computing
Cyber-Physical Systems (CPS) and Internet of Things (IoT)
Theory and Practice of Self-Organization, Self-Adaptation, and Organic Computing
Software and Systems Engineering for Autonomic and Self-Organizing Systems
Systems theory for Autonomic and Self-Organizing Systems
Data-Driven Approaches to Autonomic and Self-Organizing Systems Analysis and Management
Emerging Computing Paradigms
Socio-technical Autonomic and Self-Organizing Systems
Languages and Formal Methods for Autonomic and Self-Organizing Systems
Self-Aware, Reflective, and Cognitive Computing
Application Areas for Autonomic and Self-Organizing Systems such as Autonomous Vehicles, Smart Cities, Swarms, etc.
Assurances, security, resilience, and reliability of Autonomic and Self-Organizing Systems
Cross-disciplinary research on e.g., complex systems, control theory, artificial intelligence, chemistry, psychology, sociology, and biology
We invite authors to submit the following kinds of contributions:
Research Papers
(up to 10 pages) presenting novel ideas in the research context described
in this call,
motivated by problems from current practice or applied research.
Experience Reports
(up to 10 pages) covering innovative implementations, novel applications, interesting
performance results and experience in applying recent research advance to practical situations on any topics of
interest.
Vision Papers
(up to 6 pages) introducing ground-shaking, provocative, and even controversial ideas; discuss
long term perspectives and challenges; focus on overlooked or underrepresented areas, and foster debate.
All submissions will be rigorously peer-reviewed and evaluated based on the quality of their technical
contribution, originality, soundness, significance, presentation, understanding of the state of the art, and overall
quality.
We continue the tradition of awarding the best paper with the
Karsten Schwan Best Paper Award
; further, we
intend to provide selected papers of the conference an opportunity to publish an extended version in a
special
issue
of ACM Transactions on Autonomous and Adaptive Systems (TAAS).

text.tspan: Review criteria, special issues, artifacts evaluation, and awards

tspan.tspan: For the first time, ACSOS introduces anartifact evaluation program. Authors of accepted papers with a
computational component will have the option to submit their code and/or their data to an
optional artifact
evaluation
process. Participation in the program is optional and does not impact the paper acceptance in any
way. The best artifacts will be awarded the
IEEE ACSOS Best Software Artifact Award
All submissions are required to be formatted according to
the standard IEEE Computer Society Press proceedings
style guide. Papers are submitted electronically in PDF
format through the ACSOS 2021 EasyChair conference
management system. All papers are required to be
formatted according to the standard IEEE Computer
Society Press proceeding style guide (double column).
Research papers and experience reports will be included in
the conference proceedings that will be published by IEEE
Computer Society Press and made available as a part of
the IEEE Digital Library. Vision papers will be part of a
separate proceedings volume (the ACSOS Companion).
As per the standard IEEE policies, all submissions should
be original, i.e., they should not have been previously
published in any conference proceedings, book, or journal
and should not currently be under review for another
archival conference. We also fully abide by the IEEE’s
policies regarding plagiarism and self-plagiarism.
Where relevant and appropriate, accepted papers will also
be encouraged to participate in the Demo or Poster
Sessions.
